#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:5
msgid "Global Configuration Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:7
msgid ""
"NumPy has a few import-time, compile-time, or runtime configuration options "
"which change the global behaviour.  Most of these are related to performance "
"or for debugging purposes and will not be interesting to the vast majority "
"of users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:14
msgid "Performance-related options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:17
msgid "Number of threads used for linear algebra"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:19
msgid ""
"NumPy itself is normally intentionally limited to a single thread during "
"function calls, however it does support multiple Python threads running at "
"the same time. Note that for performant linear algebra NumPy uses a BLAS "
"backend such as OpenBLAS or MKL, which may use multiple threads that may be "
"controlled by environment variables such as ``OMP_NUM_THREADS`` depending on "
"what is used. One way to control the number of threads is the package "
"`threadpoolctl <https://pypi.org/project/threadpoolctl/>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:31
msgid "madvise hugepage on Linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:33
msgid ""
"When working with very large arrays on modern Linux kernels, you can "
"experience a significant speedup when `transparent hugepage <https://www."
"kernel.org/doc/html/latest/admin-guide/mm/transhuge.html>`_ is used. The "
"current system policy for transparent hugepages can be seen by::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:39
msgid "cat /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/enabled"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:41
msgid ""
"When set to ``madvise`` NumPy will typically use hugepages for a performance "
"boost. This behaviour can be modified by setting the environment variable::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:44
msgid "NUMPY_MADVISE_HUGEPAGE=0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:46
msgid ""
"or setting it to ``1`` to always enable it. When not set, the default is to "
"use madvise on Kernels 4.6 and newer. These kernels presumably experience a "
"large speedup with hugepage support. This flag is checked at import time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:52
msgid "SIMD feature selection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:54
msgid ""
"Setting ``NPY_DISABLE_CPU_FEATURES`` will exclude simd features at runtime. "
"See :ref:`runtime-simd-dispatch`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:59
msgid "Debugging-related options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:62
msgid "Warn if no memory allocation policy when deallocating data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:64
msgid ""
"Some users might pass ownership of the data pointer to the ``ndarray`` by "
"setting the ``OWNDATA`` flag. If they do this without setting (manually) a "
"memory allocation policy, the default will be to call ``free``. If "
"``NUMPY_WARN_IF_NO_MEM_POLICY`` is set to ``\"1\"``, a ``RuntimeWarning`` "
"will be emitted. A better alternative is to use a ``PyCapsule`` with a "
"deallocator and set the ``ndarray.base``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/global_state.rst:71
msgid "This variable is only checked on the first import."
msgstr ""
